{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503495"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.18,0.63,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104157"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42438"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104157"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents, who report a six-week history of his odd behaviour. Over this period, they report their son has become obsessed with the notion that he is being watched by government spies. Over this time, they have also found it more difficult to understand and maintain conversation with him. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon further questioning, his parents note a six-month history of withdrawn behaviour from their son, culminating in him withdrawing from his architecture degree and losing his part-time job at the supermarket.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled and agitated. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Conversation is disjointed and centres thematically on the belief that he is being monitored by government spies and is the target of an investigation. A full organic work-up, including a urine drug screen, is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brief psychotic disorder","Schizoaffective disorder","Schizophrenia","Major depressive episode with psychotic features","Drug-induced psychosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. The patient presents with both positive symptoms (paranoid delusions, disorganized speech) and negative symptoms (social withdrawal, functional decline). His six-month history of withdrawn behaviour (prodromal symptom), followed by a six-week period of paranoia (active symptoms), fulfills the diagnostic criteria for schizophrenia according to DSM-5.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrief psychotic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by the sudden onset of psychotic symptoms lasting at least 1 day but less than 1 month. In this case, the duration of symptoms (6 weeks of active symptoms, 6 months of prodromal symptoms) exceeds the criteria for brief psychotic disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizoaffective disorder\u003C/strong\u003E requires the presence of a major mood episode (depressive or manic) concurrent with symptoms of schizophrenia, as well as a period of psychosis without prominent mood symptoms. In this case, there is no mention of significant mood symptoms, making schizoaffective disorder less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor depressive episode with psychotic features\u003C/strong\u003E involves the presence of delusions or hallucinations in the context of a major depressive episode. While the patient shows some signs of functional decline, there is no clear evidence of depressed mood, anhedonia, or other core depressive symptoms, making this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-induced psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case as the urine drug screen was unremarkable, and the duration of symptoms (6 months) is longer than typically seen in substance-induced psychotic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of schizophrenia is supported by the presence of positive symptoms (delusions, disorganized speech), negative symptoms (social withdrawal), duration of symptoms (at least 6 months), significant functional impairment (withdrawal from university, job loss), and the absence of other medical or substance-related causes. Early intervention and treatment are crucial for better long-term outcomes in schizophrenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schizophrenia is characterized by positive symptoms (delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech) and negative symptoms (apathy, avolition, alogia) lasting at least 6 months, with at least 1 month of active symptoms.","Functional impairment is a key diagnostic criterion for schizophrenia, often affecting work, interpersonal relations, or self-care."],"references":["Holder SD, Wayhs A. Schizophrenia. Am Fam Physician. 2014;90(11):775-82. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25611712/","Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders. Fifth ed. Arlington, VA: American Psychiatric Association; 2013."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86480"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86480"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T16:43:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T17:09:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104157"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identif